ass B common stock. Class A shareholders get 1 vote per share, while Class B shareholders get 10 votes per share. Class B shareholders will vote together with Class A as a single class, except they have the exclusive right to elect a majority of the board of directors.\n*   **Pre-Offering Reclassifications:** Prior to the IPO, all outstanding Class C common stock will be reclassified into Class A common stock, and all preferred stock will convert into Class A and Class B common stock.\n*   **Directed Share Program (DSP):** Up to a (redacted) percent of shares are reserved for sale to certain employees, management associates, friends, and family. These shares will not be subject to lock-up restrictions.\n*   **Retail Investor Allocation:** A portion of shares will be offered to retail investors through specific online brokerage platforms, including Charles Schwab, Fidelity, Robinhood, SoFi Securities, and E*TRADE.\n*   **Lock-Up Agreements:** Existing shareholders are subject to a staggered early release schedule based on post-IPO dates, earnings releases, and stock price performance (e.g., releasing 20% after the first earnings release, with more released if the stock trades 30% above the IPO price). The Founder is excluded from these early release provisions.\n*   **Stabilization:** Morgan Stanley will act as stabilization agent and may engage in covered and naked short sales to stabilize the price of the Class A common stock post-IPO.\n\n### 4. Cover Page Details\n*   **Issuer:** Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (a Texas corporation).\n*   **Listing:** The Class A common stock has been applied to be listed on The Nasdaq Stock Market LLC (“Nasdaq”) and Nasdaq Texas, Inc. under the trading symbol **“SPCX.”**\n*   **Shares Outstanding Post-Offering:** The cover page details the outstanding shares of Class A and Class B common stock immediately after the offering (blanks in the text), alongside the respective voting power percentages of each class. \n*   **Use of 