ucture rationales for a pre-IPO split: retail affordability, round-lot alignment, liquidity enhancement, conventional pricing bands, and equity-compensation granularity. The filing reflects the split by retroactively adjusting all share and per-share information for all periods presented, with weighted-average shares and EPS figures restated on a post-split basis, the preferred-stock conversion rate proportionately adjusted, and merger exchange ratios explicitly carved out as remaining on a pre-split basis.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Note 1, fee table, prospectus preamble, underwriting section, and consolidated statements of operations"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/rules-regulations/fee-rate-advisories/2026-1",\n      "name": "SEC Section 6(b) Filing Fee Rate Advisory for Fiscal Year 2026 ($138.10 per million, effective October 1, 2025)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.ainvest.com/news/strategic-rationale-stock-splits-impact-retail-investor-participation-2512",\n      "name": "AInvest — The Strategic Rationale Behind Stock Splits and Their Impact on Retail Investor Participation"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
