    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='## The 2026 Stock Split: Rationales and Reflection in Historical Per-Share Data\n\n### 1. What the Filing Discloses About the Split\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) discloses the following about the "2026 Stock Split" in Note 1 to the consolidated financial statements:\n\n> "On May 4, 2026, the Company effected a five-for-one forward stock split of its authorized, issued, and outstanding shares of Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock (\'2026 Stock Split\'). The conversion rate of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was proportionately adjusted to factor in the 2026 Stock Split. All share and per share information has been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split for all periods presented."\n\nKey mechanical facts:\n- **Ratio:** 5-for-1 forward split\n- **Effective date:** May 4, 2026 (approximately two weeks before the S-1 filing date of May 20, 2026)\n- **Classes affected:** Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock (authorized, issued, and outstanding)\n- **Preferred stock:** Conversion rate proportionately adjusted — post-split, each share of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock converts into 50 shares of common stock\n- **Auditor emphasis:** The independent auditor\'s report carries an explanatory paragraph with an exception date of May 7, 2026, specifically referencing the stock split discussed in Note 1\n\n### 2. Typical Underwriting and Market-Structure Rationales for a Pre-IPO Split\n\n**Important disclosure caveat:** The S-1 does **not** explicitly state the rationale for the 2026 Stock Split. The filing describes only the mechanical effects. The rationales below reflect standard underwriting and market-structure practice for forward stock splits executed shortly before an IPO, supported by the offering structure disclosed elsewhere in the prospectus.\n\n**(a) Retail investor accessibility and affordability.** A forward split reduces the per-share price by the split ratio (here, dividing by 5), making individual shares more affordable to retail investors who may trade in whole shares rather than fractional units. This is particularly relevant for SpaceX, whose prospectus expressly provides for a **retail investor allocation** through online brokerage platforms — Charles Schwab, Fidelity, Robinhood, SoFi Securities, and E*TRADE — at the same IPO price as institutional allocations. A lower post-split price broadens the addressable retail order book.\n\n**(b) Board-lot and round-lot alignment.** U.S. exchanges traditionally quote and trade in round lots of 100 shares. A high nominal pre-split price can make a single round lot prohibitively expensive for many retail accounts. Splitting before the IPO aligns the post-split price with conventional round-lot economics, improving order flow granularity.\n\n**(c) Liquidity and share-count depth.** A 5-for-1 split multiplies the float fivefold. More shares outstanding at a lower price typically supports tighter bid-ask spreads, greater depth at each price level, and higher share-volume turnover — all of which underwriters value for post-IPO trading stability and for the stabilization activities disclosed in the prospectus (Morgan Stanley as stabilization agent).\n\n**(d) Conventional IPO pricing band.** Underwriters generally prefer an offering price within a range that is familiar to the market and compatible with exchange listing standards. A split executed before pricing allows the syndicate to set the IPO price on a post-split basis, avoiding an anomalously high nominal price that could deter participation or create odd-lot fragmentation.\n\n**(e) Option and equity-compensation granularity.** A lower per-share price permits finer-grained option strike prices and RSU grant sizing, which is relevant given SpaceX\'s large employee equity program and the Directed Share Program (DSP) disclosed in the prospectus for employees, management associates, friends, and family.\n\n**(f) Index and eligibility considerations.** Certain index inclusion methodologies and exchange listing criteria reference per-share price thresholds. A split can position the post-IPO stock within conventional price bands for index eligibility over time.\n\n### 3. How the Filing Reflects the Split in Historical Per-Share Data\n\nThe filing applies **retrospective retroactive adjustment** to all historical per-share data, consistent with ASC 260 (Earnings Per Share) and ASC 505 (Equity) treatment of stock splits. Specifically:\n\n**(a) Universal retroactive adjustment.** The prospectus preamble states:\n\n> "The consolidated financial statements of SpaceX have been retrospectively recast for all periods presented to include (i) the historical results of X.AI Holdings Corp.... and X Holdings Corp.... because these transactions were between entities under common control, and (ii) a five-for-one stock split of the Company\'s Class A, Class B, and Class C Common Stock, effective May 4, 2026 (the \'2026 Stock Split\'). Unless otherwise stated or the context otherwise requires, all share and per share information included in this prospectus have been retroactively adjusted to reflect the 2026 Stock Split."\n\nThis means every share count, per-share metric, weighted-average share figure, and conversion/exchange ratio in the filing is presented on a post-split (5×) basis for all historical periods, unless explicitly noted otherwise.\n\n**(b) Weighted-average shares outstanding (post-split basis, in millions):**\n\n| Period | Basic | Diluted |\n|--------|-------|---------|\n| FY 2023 | 2,759 | 2,759 |\n| FY 2024 | 2,848 | 9,956 |\n| FY 2025 | 2,926 | 2,926 |\n\nThe 2024 diluted figure (9,956 million) is elevated because 2024 was a net-income year, so dilutive securities — primarily the conversion of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock (6,771 million shares), plus stock options (292 million) and RSUs (45 million) — were included. In loss years (2023, 2025), potentially dilutive securities were anti-dilutive and excluded, so basic equals diluted. All of these share counts reflect the 5× post-split adjustment.\n\n**(c) Net income (loss) per share (post-split basis):**\n\n| Period | Basic | Diluted |\n|--------|-------|---------|\n| FY 2023 | $(1.68) | $(1.68) |\n| FY 2024 | $0.01 | $0.00 |\n| FY 2025 | $(1.69) | $(1.69) |\n\nThese per-share figures are computed using the retroactively adjusted (post-split) weighted-average share counts.\n\n**(d) Preferred stock conversion rate.** The conversion rate of SpaceX Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock was proportionately adjusted. Post-split, each share of preferred converts into 50 shares of common stock (i.e., 5× the pre-split conversion rate of 10).\n\n**(e) Merger exchange ratios — explicit "pre-split" carve-out.** The filing explicitly flags that certain merger mechanics remain on a pre-split basis. The xAI Merger exchange ratio (0.1433 shares of SpaceX stock per xAI share) and the $75.46 cash election per share are noted as being on a "pre-2026 Stock Split basis." This is the principal exception to the universal retroactive adjustment and is disclosed to avoid confusion when comparing merger consideration to post-split share counts.\n\n**(f) Auditor\'s report emphasis.** The independent auditor\'s report includes an emphasis-of-matter paragraph with an exception date of May 7, 2026, drawing attention to the stock split effects described in Note 1 — a standard procedure when a significant non-recurring capital-structure event occurs between the balance-sheet date and the audit report date.\n\n### 4. Summary\n\nThe 2026 Stock Split was a 5-for-1 forward split effective May 4, 2026, executed approximately two weeks before the S-1 filing. While the filing does **not** explicitly state the rationale, the offering structure — including a dedicated retail allocation through major online brokerages, a Directed Share Program, and stabilization arrangements — is consistent with the standard underwriting and market-structure rationales for a pre-IPO split: retail affordability, round-lot alignment, liquidity enhancement, conventional pricing bands, and equity-compensation granularity. The filing reflects the split by retroactively adjusting all share and per-share information for all periods presented, with weighted-average shares and EPS figures restated on a post-split basis, the preferred-stock conversion rate proportionately adjusted, and merger exchange ratios explicitly carved out as remaining on a pre-split basis.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Note 1, fee table, prospectus preamble, underwriting section, and consolidated statements of operations"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/rules-regulations/fee-rate-advisories/2026-1",\n      "name": "SEC Section 6(b) Filing Fee Rate Advisory for Fiscal Year 2026 ($138.10 per million, effective October 1, 2025)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.ainvest.com/news/strategic-rationale-stock-splits-impact-retail-investor-participation-2512",\n      "name": "AInvest — The Strategic Rationale Behind Stock Splits and Their Impact on Retail Investor Participation"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
